'''Kerri''' was a [[human]] [[Gender|female]] who lived on the [[planet]] [[Kenari]] with her brother [[Cassian Jeron Andor|Kassa]]. At a young age, Kerri was [[Exploratory mission to investigate a downed craft|separated]] from her brother, who was taken offworld and later became known as Cassian Andor. Many years later, Andor still searched for his long-lost sister.

==Biography==
Kerri was a [[human]] [[Gender|female]] who lived with her brother [[Cassian Jeron Andor|Kassa]] in a [[Kenari Village|village]] on the [[planet]] [[Kenari]].<ref name="Kassa" /> When she was six [[Standard year|years]] old,<ref name="Databank">{{Databank|kerri|Kerri}}</ref> Kassa joined a party of villagers [[Exploratory mission to investigate a downed craft|going to investigate]] the crash site of a [[transpo corsair]], while Kerri was left behind.<ref name="Kassa" /> Kassa did not return from the mission<ref name="Databank" /> as he became separated from the group and was taken offworld by [[Maarva Carassi Andor|Maarva]] and [[Clem Andor]], who wanted to rescue him from danger.<ref name="Reckoning">{{Andor|Reckoning (episode)}}</ref> From Kerri's perspective, her brother had vanished after the mission, leaving her behind.<ref name="Databank" />

[[Standard year|Years]] later, Kassa, now known as Cassian Andor, lived with Maarva on the planet [[Ferrix]]. However, he still [[Search for Kerri|searched]] for his sister and eventually traveled to a [[Leisure Zone brothel|brothel]] on [[Morlana One]] in [[5 BBY]], having heard there was a girl from Kenari working there. However, after consulting one of the [[Unidentified brothel hostess|hostesses]], he learned that the girl from Kenari had left [[Standard month|months]] before.<ref name="Kassa" />

After taking part in the [[Aldhani heist|heist]] at [[Aldhani]], Andor returned to Ferrix, where he was told by Maarva to stop searching for his sister, saying that everyone had been killed on Kenari and reminding him that what had happened to his home and to Kerri was not his fault.<ref name="Announcement">{{Andor|Announcement}}</ref> Andor's partner [[Bix Caleen]] was aware of Kerri's existence.<ref name="Ever Been">{{Andor|Ever Been to Ghorman?}}</ref>

While living at the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic|Rebel Alliance's]] [[Great Temple|base]] on the [[moon]] [[Yavin 4]] in [[1 BBY]], Andor had a dream of his sister that was interrupted when his [[KX-series security droid|droid]] companion [[K-2SO]] woke him from his slumber.<ref name="JKE">{{Andor|Jedha, Kyber, Erso}}</ref>

{{Char-stub}}

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|<nowiki></nowiki>''[Kerri]'' also motivates a lot of future behavior when we really get into it. The idea of leaving people behind and what it costs him to leave things behind. That's gonna become a big issue as we move to the second half, the fear of being someone who leaves someone behind and what that costs him.|Tony Gilroy|<ref name="Podcast 555">{{WebCite|url=https://podfollow.com/empire-podcast/episode/c8bb4ca64cd6e84b1db83dd8c3163afb7f98ad77/view|text=The Empire Film Podcast 555|archivedate=20231128204144}}</ref>}}
Kerri first appeared in the [[Kassa (episode)|first episode]] of the live-action [[Disney+]] series ''[[Star Wars: Andor]]''. She was portrayed by [[Belle Swarc]].<ref name="Kassa" /> Interviewed for The Empire Film Podcast episode 555, [[Tony Gilroy]]&mdash;when asked if the search for Kerri was a seed for the future or a red herring&mdash;stated that the answer was complicated. He did state that Kerri set up the fear of losing something or someone, and everything that entails, which he said was a concept explored in [[Andor Season 2|''Andor'' Season 2]].<ref name="Podcast 555" /> Gilroy had originally intended to resolve the plot thread around Kerri either himself or by allowing another writer to tackle it, but he found himself unsure of how to continue the search storyline when he thought on it. Indeed, he later reflected he had "some melodramatic version" of its resolution that he scrapped from season 2. Instead, he came to believe that not addressing what happened to Kerri left a hole in Cassian Andor's life that he was never able to fill, thereby helping to establish Cassian as someone who would always try to go back and find people. To Gilroy, using Kerri's absence as the catalyst of Cassian's savior complex was more interesting than any resolution.<ref name="Deadline">{{WebCite|url=https://deadline.com/2025/05/andor-season-2-finale-tony-gilroy-1236387522|text=Tony Gilroy On The ‘Andor’ Season 2 Finale, Cassian’s Sister & Disrupting ‘Star Wars’ Canon|date=2025-05-13|author=D'Alessandro, Anthony|work=''Deadline''|archiveurl=https://archive.ph/4bBcO}}</ref>

Kerri ultimately did not appear in Season 2, a choice that Gilroy felt was appropriate for Cassian's character. Although he acknowledged that people wanted the sibling storyline to be resolved, Gilroy maintained that Kerri served Cassian's character better by being absent. He said that such a deficit created a void for Cassian that was the reason he chose to be heroic and selfless to others.<ref name="Hollywood">{{WebCite|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/tv/tv-news/andor-finale-twists-tony-gilroy-interview-1236212162|text='Andor' Creator Tony Gilroy on Series Finale's Biggest Moves and 'Rogue One' Links|date=2025-05-14|author=Hibberd, James|work=[[Wikipedia:The Hollywood Reporter|''The Hollywood Reporter'']]|archivedate=20250516052409}}</ref>

